ÅCHAPTER3

THESECULARTRADITION:NARRATIVEANDDEFINITIVEMOTIFS
Ä
Wearenowreadytoexplorethemotifswhichgrewupand
flourishedinEnglandduringtheMiddleAges.Somelinkswith
previoustraditionareoftenevident,butthemotifsare
essentiallynew:theirformisradicallyalteredandtheir
purposetransformedtosuittheinterestsandrequirementsof
Englishauthorsandtheiraudiences.

Itisdifficulttofindacohesivestructurewhichcan
accommodateacomprehensivestudyofthewidelydisseminated
huntingmotifs.Theirappearanceinalargenumberoftextsof
differenttypesprecludesasystematicconsiderationbygenre.
Butastudyofthemotifsrevealsaregularpatternofusewhich
dividesthemapproximatelyintosecularandreligious.Thoughthe
distinctionisnottotallyrigid,itishelpfulasastarting
point,soweshalllookattheseculartraditioninthischapter
andthereligiousmotifsinChapter4.

Therearetwodistincttypesofsecularmotifs:huntingepisodes
andimagesmayserveanarrativefunction,furtheringthe
developmentoftheplot,ormayhelptodefineacharacter's
personalityandrole.Thereligiousmotifsdevelopasingle
idea:thehuntbringstothetextaseriesofassociationsand
connotationsrevolvingaroundthehuntasrepresentativeof
worldlypreoccupation.However,theusestowhichwritersputthe
motifscannotalwaysbecategorisedassimplyasthis.Amore
talentedwritercouldcombineallthree-the'narrative',
'definitive'and'associative'functions-inasingleepisode,
andthebestwriterstaketheirexplorationofamotiffarbeyond
itsusuallimits.Thedistinctionbetweensecularandreligious
motifsimposesananachronisticpolarityonthetexts.Much
medievalliteraturedoesnotfallsimplyintoonecategoryorthe
other,andnosuchcleardivisioncouldhavebeenpossibleor
necessaryintheMiddleAges-themedievalreadercouldhappily
accommodatethereligiousandprofanesidebysidewithoutany
qualms.Consequently,wewillsometimesfindthatworkswhich
wouldnormallybeconsideredsecular,usehuntingmotifswhich
arefoundpredominantlyinareligiouscontext.Suchexamplesare
consideredinthenextchapteralongsidethereligiousworks
whichuseanalogousmotifs.Thereisfurtherblurringofthe
categoriesasdifferentwritersviewtheconnotationsof
courtlinessdifferently.Whatonepoetseesaslaudablecivility
anotherseesassinfulostentation,yetbothholdupastheir
examplethesamefigure:thecourtlyhunterinhisfinery.


ÅNarrativeanddescriptionÄ

Thenarrativeusesofthehunthavenotbeennotedbefore,
despitetheirfrequency,probablybecausetheyaregivenonly
rudimentarydevelopmentasincidentsintheirownright.The
Äusualformisofoneortwolinesevokingthehunt,followedby
theintroductionofanadventure:

     ...'wharis˛eking?'
     ...'anhonting,
     Wi˛kingesfiftene'.ê04,1Ä

     WhyleTorrentanhuntyngwaseê03,2Ä

     TheKinghimrodanhuntingeê06,3Ä

     [BernardMassingerewas]
     Huntyngafturanhyndeê03,4Ä

     ﬁaidi#thimwi˛-outendueling,
     Fortowendeondere-hunting,
     &buskedhemfortoride.ê03,5Ä

Theconventionalformofthebriefreferencetothehunt
occasionallyspecifiesthepreyand/ormentionsthehunters'
preparations,butdoesnotexpanduponthehunt'sprogress.Where
thehuntepisodeisgivengreaternarrativedevelopmentinits
ownright,itgenerallyhasasecondaryfunctiondeveloping
character.

Whenhuntingmotifsareusedtodefinecharacter,theprogressof
thehuntbecomesimportant,asthehunter'spersonalityis
developedthroughhisconductinit.Thehuntmostoftenusedin
thiswayistheboar-hunt,sincethedangeroftheconfrontation
allowsthewritertodemonstrateboththemartialprowessand
courtlyskillofthehero.Theconsistentstructuralpatterning
ofthismotiffromoneromancetoanotherreinforcesits
amplificationoftheheroinlinewithconventionalchivalric
