E
Ävaluesbyrecallingsimilarmotifsandtheirheroes.However,a
deer-huntmaybeemployedtoshowcowardiceorfollyinthe
character,ortodemonstrateonlycourtlyskillwithoutthe
warrior-likequalitiesoftheboar-hunter.

Theassociativeusesofthehuntdescribedinthenextchapter
againdonotgenerallydeveloptheepisodetoanygreatextent,
althoughagroupofdetailedtreatmentsinalliterativeverse
formanimportantexception.Often,theassociationsofthehunt
aretobededucedfromthebriefestmentionofthepastime.
Closelyalliedwiththisarebriefmentionsofthehunttoevoke
courtliness.Thesebecameformulaicandextremelyconcise,
comparablewiththeÑreverderieÄmotifinlyricpoetryasameans
ofcallingupanestablishedsetofassociations.

Inthischapterweshalllookatthreenarrativemotifs-a
meetingwhilehunting,theunfortunatehunt,andaseductionor
abductioninthehunter'sabsence-andfourdefinitivemotifs-
theepicboar-hunter,thecowardlyorfoolishhunter,the
proficienthunter,andthecourtlyhunter.Itisthelastof
thesethatsharessomeofthefeaturesoftheassociativemotifs
describedinthenextchapter.Itdrawsonpre-existing
associationsofcourtlyleisuretosuggestthenoblecharacterof
thehunter,evokingthesamequalitieswhicharecondemnedor
criticisedinareligiouscontext.


ÅThehuntandadventure:narrativehuntingmotifsÄ

Themostfrequentlyoccurringnarrativefunctionofthehuntin
secularliteratureisasthemeansofbeginninganadventure.The
huntiseitherinterruptedorleadsthehunterintoisolation,
andsomeadventurefollows.Thehuntisquicklyleftbehind,but
remainsavitalconstituentinthetextswhichusethemotif.

Afittingintroductiontothehuntasthenaturalpreludeto
adventureisfoundinanepisodeinMalory'sÑMorteDarthurÄ.
Earlyinthework,thehuntisusedtointroducenotonlya
singleadventurebuttheentireconceptofÑaventureÄ.Thetermsin
whichadventureisfirstdefinedinthisearlyepisodeareto
standfortheremainderofthework,augmentedbylaterevents,
butunalteredinessence.

TheadventureofthewhitehartinthetaleofTorreandPellinor
(BookIII,chapter1)beginswhenahuntforcesitsattention
uponthecourt.AsArthur'scourtpreparetoeatthefeast
celebratinghismarriagetoGuinevere,awhitehartentersthe
hallfollowedbyawhitebrachetandthirtycoupleofblack
hounds.Aknightcarriesoffthebrachet,aladycomesinand
complains,butisherselftakenawaybyanotherknight.Arthuris
gladofthis-'whanshewasgonethekyngewasgladde,forshe
madesuchanoyseê'Ä(I,p.103,lines11-12).Thisismorethana
jokeaboutArthur'sdislikeofcommotion,asemergesinMerlin's
wordsimmediatelyafterwards:
Ä
'Nay',seydeMerlion,'yemaynatlevehitso,thysadventure,so
lyghtly,forthesadventuresmustebebroughttoanende,other
ellishitwollbedisworshyptoyouandtoyourefeste.'(I,p.103,
lines13-16)

ThispassageistoresoundthroughouttheÑMorteDarthurÄ,asthe
ensuingeventsestablishthecourt'sdevotiontoadventure.In
otherhuntingmotifsinMalory'swork,themomentumofthehunt
remainsasignificantelement,anditsassociationwithadventure
isimportanteveninepisodeswheretheprimaryinterestisnot
narrative.

Theconductoftheknightsinthethreeadventureswhichfollow
thehuntinTorreandPelinorprefiguresthebestandworst
aspectsofArthurianchivalry,andtheepisodeshowsalready
presentintheRoundTablefellowshipthegermsofbothits
greatesttriumphsandthefatewhichwilleventuallyovertakeit.
ItisadismalandinauspiciousstarttotheRoundTable's
history,withGawainbeheadinganinnocentwomanandPellinor
allowinghisdaughtertodie.Blindobedienceandmercilesspride
predominate,butitisadefinitivechapteranditsforeboding
contentisofvitalsignificance.

Thisistheepitomeofthehunt'sliteraryroleasan
introductiontoadventure;theeruptionofthehuntintoArthur's
courtsignifiesthecourt'sobligationtodevoteitselfto
adventure-theycan'tescapethisadventure-thatisovertly
statedbyMerlin:'yemaynatlevehitso,thysadventure,so
lyghtly,forthesadventuresmustebebroughttoanende'.Soit
becomesthedestinyanddutyofeveryindividualandofthecourt
asawholeto'taketheadventure...thatGodwollordayne'.

Inthisepisode,Maloryinvertsaconventionalmotif,the
'meetingwhilehunting',toshowthehuntforcingitsattention
uponthecourtwhich,itseems,wouldhappilyavoidthehurly-
burlyanddisruptionofchivalricadventure,preferringthe
indulgenceofleisurelycourtlife.Inorderforthistypeof
inversiontobeeffective,Malorymusthavehadcomplete
confidenceinhisaudience'sfamiliaritywiththeassociationof
thehuntwithadventure.Howtheseassociationscametodevelop
duringthecenturyandahalfbeforehewrote,weshallnow
consider.

Ñ(1)MeetingswhileorafterhuntingÄ

Themostwidespreadnarrativehuntingmotifshowsahunter
meetinganothercharacterduringorafterahunt.Inpart,this
motifdrawsonreallife,foramedievalhuntermightwellmeet
someoneinthewoods.Whentransposedintoliterature,the
realisticstartingpointallowsanimaginativedesire(foran
affair,oranadventure)tobefulfilledcredibly.The
realisationofthedesirethroughthesubsequentnarrativeis
lentplausibilitybythefictionbeingrootedinthefamiliar
Äexperienceofthehunt.Thehuntisvitaltotheaudience's
acceptanceofthefiction,actingasasolidbasisforthe
adventure,andforgingalinkbetweenfantasyandreality.Yet
thehunthasgenerallybeenignoredandtakenforgrantedon
accountofthespeedwithwhichitisleftbehindasthe
adventuredevelops.

Themeetingwhilehuntingisusuallyaccidental,thoughinsome
instancesitiscontrived.Therearethreegeneralsub-categories
ofthemotif:thehuntermaymeetawomanwhobecomeshis
mistressorwife;orhemayhaveameetingwhichfurthershis
chivalriccareer,oftenbyleadingtohimhelpinganother
character;or,ifthehunterisaminorcharacterinthestory,
hemayfindawomanand/orchildwhomhethenadopts.Thewoman
isusuallythemotherofthehero,andthemotifisusedto
introducethechild(orhismother)toanewguardian.

Severalromancecharactersmeettheirfuturemistressorwife
afterahunt.Themoreinterestingexamplesarefoundin
ÑGenerydesÄ,theÑRomansofPartenayÄandÑPartonopeofBloisÄ.ê04,6Ä
AuferiousinÑGenerydesÄbecomeslostwhilehuntingandmeetsthe
faerySereynewhorevealsthetreacheryofhiswifeandsteward.
ShetellshimhemustsleepwithherandbegetGenerydeswhowill
workwonders.ê03,7ÄIntheÑRomansofPartenayÄ,RaymondandLord
Ameriebecomelostonahunt.LordAmerieiskilledbyaboar,
andRaymondthenmeetsMelusinewhosayshemustmarryher.ê03,8Ä
PartonopeofBloisbecomeslostonaboar-huntandthenwanders
aimlessly,travelsinashipandfinallyarrivesatanapparently
emptycastle.Heiswinedanddinedbyinvisibleattendantsand
ledtobedwherehefindshisfaerymistressMelior.ê03,9
Ä
Weshouldnotconfusethismeetingmotifwiththetraditionof
thelove-hunt.Innoinstanceisthehunteractivelyseekinga
sexualencounter,andinallcasesthewomanpresentsherselfto
himandtellshimwhathemustdo.Thereisnoattemptbythe
writersoftheromancestodrawaparallelbetweenthepursuitof
thehuntedbeastandofawoman.OnlyinÑPartonopeofBloisÄmight
wesuspectthatloveisaspredatoryasthecourtlyhunter.But
althoughMeliormayorchestratethehuntandPartonope'svoyage,
N006:005702140004
ÄInÑKingHenryÄ,thekingisvisitedinhishuntinglodgebya
hideoushagwhotestshisgenerosityandfinallyturnsintoa
beautifulwomanwhenhegrantsallherrequests.

