Äsheisnothuntinghim.Thereisnoeagerpursuitoneitherpart
tosuggestahuntmetaphor-andatmostwemaysupposethat
Partonopeisthevictim,beingluredintoatrap.Whenhe
eventuallyfindshimselfinbedwithMelior,shesayshemustnot
touchher.Hisconsequentrapeofherconfusesstillfurtherany
allusiontothelove-huntmetaphor,sincetherolesofhunterand
quarrymustshiftconstantlyinthesequencefromPartonope's
hunttotheeventualactofrape.Instead,theemphasisin
ÑPartonopeÄ,asintheotherexamples,isonestablishingthe
hero'ssolitudeandpsychologicalreadinessforasexual
relationship.Thehuntputshiminthewayoffortune-whilethe
hunterisintheforestheisinlimbo,vulnerableandready-
andfortunefrequentlyseizestheopportunity.

Whenopportunitydoesnotleadtolove,itoftenleadstoa
developmentinthehero'schivalriccareer.Inmanyromances,a
newadventureorcampaignensuesfromameetingduringahunt.
ThusGuyofWarwickishuntingwhenhemeetsmerchantswhotell
himofthesiegeofConstantinople,afterwhichhegoestothe
aidoftheemperor.ê05,10ÄSirTriamourandSirEglamourboth
undertakesinglecombatsforfigurestheymeetafterhunts.ê05,11Ä
Malory'sSirTristramagreestodobattlewithPalomedesafter
meetinghimwhilehunting(II,59,23).TheSowdonofBabylonis
huntingonthesea-shorewhenheencountersamerchantship;this
meetingprecipitatesthewarwithRomeinwhichheeventually
dies.ê04,12ÄLybeausDesconusencountersaslainknightwhileout
huntingandthisinspireshimtoembarkonachivalric
career.ê04,13ÄAlltheseexamples,likethemeetingswithawifeor
mistress,showthehuntprecedingamajorchangeinthehunter's
life.

Aspecialtypeofmeetinghasthehunterdiscoverafoundling.In
ÑSirEglamourofArtoisÄandÑWilliamofPalerneÄ,aninfantisfound
