E
ˇÄbyahuntingking.ê04,14ÄInÑSirTriamourÄboththeheroandhis
motherarefoundandadoptedbyahunter,andinÑTorrentof
PortyngaleÄonlyTorrent'smother,Desonell,isfoundbyahunting
kingwhothentakescareofher.ê15,15ÄHerethemotifispartof
thehunter'snarrative,notthefoundling's(orhero's)narrative
whichis,literally,adifferentstory.Theverseromancesare
usuallyquiteovertlyconcernedwiththestoryofonecentral
character,orsometimesofacouple,andweareonlyrarely
invitedtospeculateonthepossibilityofanothercharacter's
story,butthefoundlingmotifgivessuchanopportunity.The
familiarityofthefigureofahunterridingouttoasurprise
meetingissufficienttoarouseinterestinhisstoryevenwhen
thehunterisnottheprincipalcharacter.Oneeffectofthese
glimpsesofalternativeorperipheralnarrativesistoknitthe
centralstoryintoawholemythicbackground.Weseenotan
isolatedseriesofevents,butasequenceselectedfromawhole
worldofstorylargeenoughandcomplexenoughtoappearasa
paralleltotherealworld;itisimpossibletopulloutasingle
threadofnarrativewithoutfibresofthebackgroundfabric
clingingtoit.SoportionsofthestoriesofthekingofIsrael,
thekingofJerusalemorofSirBernardMassengere,whowas
'Huntyngafturanhynde'ê02,16ÄwhenhefoundMargaretandTriamour,
appearinthenarrativeswhichproperlybelongtothefoundlings.
Wherethenewcharacterhasasubstantialparttoplayinthe
subsequentunfoldingofthestory,thefragmentofbackground
providedbythehuntofferssuperficialsatisfactionforour
curiosity.Itprovideshimwithbothacourtlycontextandan
immediatepastthatisbriefenoughtomaintainthemomentumof
thesinglenarrative;anyadditionstothenarrativearenot
allowedtobringalonglooseend.

