ÄInÑTheWeddyngeofSirGawenandDameRagnellÄ,Arthuris
huntingwhenhemeetsGromerSomerJourewhothreatenstokill
himunlesshecandiscovertheanswertothequestion'whatdo
womenmostdesire'inayear.Thisromancegivesconsiderable
developmenttotheinitialhunt,andArthurpointsoutthathe
isonlyinhishuntinggearanditwouldbedishonourableif
GromerSomerJourekilledhimunarmed.Thepoemismildly
alliterative,anditsextensivetreatmentofthehuntmaybe
linkedtoalliterativeroots.Weshallseeinthenextchapter
thatalliterativepoetryisdistinguishedbygivingfulland
detaileddescriptionsofthehuntscenesitemploys.

E
Äleisure,occasionallyhemaybedistraught,butinanycaseheis
ready,physicallyandpsychologicallyforanewcourseofaction.
Thisreadinessforameeting,thedesireforadventure,is
expressedandfulfilledwithinanaturalisticsettingasthe
huntingexpeditionprovidesthenecessaryopportunity.

Inmedievalliterature,andintheromancesinparticular,the
huntcanleadtothemarginsofexperience,toadventureand
sometimesdeath.Itservesasatransitionalactivitywhich
allowstheherotopassfromtheordinarytothefantastic,to
leavehisfamiliarworldandenterintoanewone.Therearemany
formsthetransitionmaytake;itmayinvolveactualsocial
change(marriage,forinstance),orarevelationwhich
irrevocablyaltersthehero'sperceptionofhislife.In
ÑGenerydesÄ,Auferiousreturnstocourtafterhismeetingwith
Sereyne,buthehasreplacedhiscontentment,complacencyand
ignorancewithsorrowandwisdom.Bycontrast,thehuntin
ÑPartonopeÄseverstheherofromhisoriginalworldmoreliterally:
returningtothecourtisimpossiblebecauseheiscompletely
lost,andeventsarebeyondhiscontrol.Thesameistrueof
RaymondintheÑRomansofPartenayÄ;heislost,andfeels
responsibleforAmerie'sdeath.Hecannotgobacktohisformer
stateandisonlyabletoreturntocourtwhenMelusinegiveshim
instructions.

Morefrequently,theprotagonist'soriginalworldisnotforcibly
removed;itmaybealtered,orhemaychoosetoleaveit.Thus
LybeausDesconus,discoveringaslainknightwhenhunting,is
introducedtochivalryandleaveshislifeintheforest.His
discoverymakeshispreviouslycontentrurallifeseem
inadequate.Othersbeginanimportantadventurewhichdrastically
changestheirlives,asdotheEarlofToulouseandtheSowdonof
Babylon,whobeginadventureswhichleadrespectivelytomarriage
anddeath.ê02,19Ä

Meetingswhilehuntingdonotalwayscomeatthebeginningofa
romance,however.Ameetingsometimesintroducesanewadventure
inaseries,exploitingthehero'sleisuretobringhimintothe
nextstageofhisnarrative.ThusGuyofWarwickbecomesinvolved
inthesiegeofConstantinople,andTriamourbecomeshisfather's
champion.ÑGuyofWarwickÄusesthehuntrepeatedlytointroducea
newdeparture,settingupapatternofchivalricassociations
withinthetextwhichthepoetuseswhenGuy'schivalryis
finallyquestioned(seebelow,page00).Whenthehuntoccursin
themiddleofastory,thechangeinthehunter'slifeisnotas
drastic,butthehuntmarksahiatusintheaction.Whenonetask
isaccomplished,andanotherhasnotyetpresenteditself,a
characterhunts,makinghimselfavailableforachancemeetingin
theforestwhichmayprecipitatethenextepisodeinhisstory.
ThehuntiscomparablewithMalory'sdeviceofthequesting
N019:001003640002
ÑEarlofToulouseÄ,lines...;ÑSowdoneofBabyloneÄ,lines49ff.

E
Äknight,butinsteadofactivelyseekingadventure,thehunter
waitsforittocometohim-itusuallydoes,andhemustthen
maketherightchoiceandtakeupthechallenge.

Whenahunterencountersacharacterorevent,hishuntis
interruptedandhefollowshisnewadventure.Thisisasit
shouldbe,forthedemandsofloveormilitaryserviceare
superiortothoseofhuntingandalaudablecharacterrenounces
thechaseformoreimportantconsiderations.Huntingenhancesa
characteratleisure,bringingassociationsofnobilityand
courtliness,butthehunter'scharacterisfurtherenhancedwhen
heleavesthehunttotakeuphisnewcourseofaction,showing
thathehashisprioritiesright.Asweshallseelater,this
interestinprioritiesdevelopedindependentlyintoamotif
denouncingorridiculingcharacterswhodonotrecognisethatthe
huntshouldoccupyalowerplaceintheirschemeofvaluesthan
loveorwar.Asimilarinterestinthecorrectplaceofhunting
inacharacter'sschemeofvaluesisdemonstratedinthe
religioustreatmentsweshalllookatinthenextchapter.

Becausethehuntsarealwaysabandonedafterameeting,theymay
seemtobeunimportant.Indeed,fortheheroofchivalric
romance,huntingisunimportantwhenthedemandsofloveor
militaryservicetakeprecedence.Butinthestructureofthe
episodes,huntinghasasignificantparttoplay.Onthemost
elementarylevel,itprovidesthenarrativeframeworkwhich
allowsameetingtotakeplace.Thehuntgivesthestory
coherenceandplausibility,providingareasonforthehunterto
beintheforest.Butbyrepeateduseofthemotif,thehunt
becametheacceptedsettingforcoincidences,andsoaftera
whilethosecoincidenceswhichoccurredonahuntwererendered
immediatelycrediblebytheweightofconvention.Theadvantage
ofthehuntderivesfromitsubiquityandordinariness(yet
inherentinterest).Thehuntingcharacterandhisadventure
requirenofurtherjustificatorycausationorspecial
explanation.


(2):Theunfortunatehunt

Almostascommonasthemeetingmotifisthemotifofthe
unfortunatehunt.Again,thehunter'sisolationandtemporary
exclusionfromnormalsocietyofferastartingpoint,butnowhis
readinessforanewdepartureisdevelopedasvulnerability.This
vulnerabilitymayleadtohisdownfallintheforest,ortosome
catastropheathomeinhisabsence.Themotifisfrequently
associatedwithtreachery,withanenemyexploitingeitherhis
isolationorhisabsencefromcourt.

Theunfortunatehunthasseveralfunctionsinromance.Inits
simplestform,itallowstheplottomovetothenextstage,but
oftenitalsoennoblesthehero,orprovidesmotivationforlater
actions.InÑBevesofHamtounÄ,theÑRomansofPartenayÄandÑGuyof
WarwickÄthemotifperformsallthesefunctionsatonce.Atthe
ÄstartofBevesofHamtoun,thehero'sfatherissentonaboar-
huntbecausehissickwifeneedsamedicinemadefromaboar.But
thehuntispartofhertreacherousplot,andheismurderedby
herlover.Thisincidentpavesthewayforthebanishmentof
Beves,whoisresentfulofhisnewstepfather,andprovideshis
latermotivationforkillinghim.ItalsoenhancesBeves'sown
characterwhenhesurpasseshisfather'saction,latersucceeding
inkillingadangerousboarandthefosterswhothenattack
him.ê04,20ÄIntheÑRomansofPartenayÄ,Raymondandhislord,Amerie,
becomelostonahunt.Amerieiskilledbytheboartheyare
pursuing,butRaymondeventuallykillstheanimal.Althoughthis
huntisparticularlyunfortunateforAmerie,itisalso
unfortunateforRaymond,whoisdistraughtatthelossofhis
lord,afraidofbeingaccusedofmurderinghim,andislostand
benightedintheforest.ê03,21ÄThepredominantfunctionofAmerie's
deathistoisolateRaymondreadyforhisownadventurebut,in
addition,hisdeathdemonstratestheboar'sferocityandsoalso
magnifiesRaymond'sheroismwhenhefinallydefeatsit.WhenGuy
ofWarwickhuntsagiganticboarintoaprivateforestand
killstheowner'ssoninaquarrel,hehastotakeonvarious
furtherfightsasaresult.ê02,22ÄThisisamajorturningpointin
theromance,andthemisfortunenotonlyintroducessubsequent
eventsbutmarksthepointatwhichallthevirtuesassociated
withthenoblehunterarebroughtintoquestion.Thisepisodeis
discussedatlengthbelowwithotherexamplesofthe'epic'boar-
huntmotif.

Usually,misfortuneduringahuntennoblesthehunterinsomeway,
thoughthisisnotalwaysthecase.Themisfortunecantakemany
forms.ForOtesdeLile,itisdefeatatthehandsofLybaeus
Desconus,whotakesoneofhishuntinghoundsandthensubdues
Otesinaduel.ê04,23ÄAswiththefoundlingepisodes,thehuntgives
OtesdeLileaswiftandnaturalintroductionintothepoemwith
ascrapofnarrativepastassignedtohim,and,inessence,this
adventureissimilartothatofcharacterswhohavefortunate
meetings,suchasSirBernardMassengereinÑSirTriamourÄ.While
hunting,OtesdeLileisvulnerable,butinsteadoffindinga
childhemeetsLybeaus;theparticularfateofthesusceptible
hunterisamatterofluck.
