huntingwhenIpomadonreturnstotheSciliancourtdisguisedasa
foolishknightandleavesunrecognisedandridiculedbecausethe
onepersonwhowouldhaveknownhimisabsent.ê03,30ÄMisfortuneofa
moreseriouskindbefallswhenBevesofHamtoungoeshunting,
leavingIocyaninacavewithBonefaceandBeves'shorse:two
lionseatBonefaceandthehorse,thoughtheylieatIocyan's
feet,unabletoharmaroyalvirgin.ê02,31Ä

Theremaysometimesbeahintofcensureintheseexamples,
whetherornottreacheryisinvolved;whileabsenthunting,the
hunterisnegligentofhisduties-whetherashusband,guardian
orruler-andsoinvitesdisaster.Buthisill-luckhasasecond
aspect:hisimportanceisstressedasmisfortunecannotbe
counteredifheisaway.Thisennoblestheheroifheis
betrayed,andsimultaneouslybelittlestheenemieswhoexploit
thelapseinhisvigilance.Theimplicationisthattheywould
notdareconfronttheherohonourably.

Huntingcanoftenbeseensimplyas'preoccupation';thehunt
itselfisusuallyoflittlesignificanceandisnotdescribedin
detail.Butitistheconventionalmeansofremovingacharacter
fromthescene,anditisclearthattomedievalwritersand
audiencesitwasespeciallyappropriateandacceptableinthis
role.Thevulnerabilityofthehunterwassufficientlywell-
establishedforMalorytobeabletouseitinanepisodein
whichLaBeallIsodereprimandsTristramforhuntingunarmed:

'Imervaylememuchethatyeremembirnatyoureselffhowyebe
