TheimaginativeprojectionofbetrayalinIsode'sarticulationof
theriskreliesheavilyupontheestablishedtraditionof
misfortune-andparticularlytreachery-befallingthe
susceptiblehunter.

Whileacharacterishuntingheisremovedfromthesafeand
civilisedsocietyofthecourtandwandersfreelyinthe
dangerouswildernessoftheforest.Thepathofthehunteris
controlledonlybythevagariesofthebeasthehunts,andchance
playsasubstantialpartintheoutcome.Thevulnerabilityofthe
hunterasitappearsinliteraturecertainlyechoesthedangers
ofthehuntinreallife,butiscompactedwithapsychological
vulnerabilitystemmingfromthehunter'sexclusionfromthe
familiarandorganisedinstitutionofsocietyandhispenetration
intothechaosoftheforest.Togohuntingcanbetochallenge
theunknown,adeclarationofreadinessandself-sufficiency,
whichmayhaveagoodorbadoutcome.Thevulnerabilityofthose
heleavesbehind,andtheweaknessoftheenemiesthatexploit
hisabsence,aretestamenttothehunter'spersonalstrengthand
importance.


ÑSeductionandabductioninthehunter'sabsenceÄ

Aspecialsubgroupoftheunfortunatehuntwarrantsseparate
considerationbecauseofthefrequencywithwhichitappears.
Itinvolvestheseductionorabductionofthehunter'swife,
daughterorbelovedwhileheishunting.Torrent'slossof
Desonell,andthebetrayalofHornandRimenhildarerelatedto
thismotif,whichencompassesexamplesofseduction,abduction
andelopement.Oneimportantdistinctionshouldbemadebetween
examplesofthismotif:insomeinstancesthewomaninstigatesor
iscomplicitinthedeceptionofthehunterandinotherssheis
anunwillingvictim.

Seductionduringthehunter'sabsenceisalwaysinstigatedbythe
woman.ThusinÑAmisandAmilounÄ,Belisaunttwiceattemptsto
seduceAmisinherfather'sabsencehunting,threateningwhenhe
refuseshertoclaimthathehasrapedher.ê02,32ÄAnotherexampleof
this'Potiphar'swife'motifoccursinÑGenerydesÄ.Serenydes
(Generydes'step-mother)triestoseduceGenerydeswhileher
husbandisawayhunting.Whenherejectsheradvances,shetears
herclothesandtellsthestewardthatGenerydesassaultedher.ê02,33Ä
