detailthaninÑSirGawainandtheGreenKnightÄ.ê04,35ÄIneachof
theseexamples,themanisunwilling.Theonlyherotocomply
withthewoman'swishesisAmis,whorelentsonthesecond
occasion(underduress).Theencounterdevelopsintoanenduring
relationship,butthecoupleareobservedbythesteward,who
thenplotsagainstthem.

Intheseexamples,theburdenofguiltfallsonthehunter's
relative.Itisnotarbitraryfortunewhichactsagainsthim,but
thewomanherselfwhoundertakesacourseofactionpotentially
hurtfultothehunter.(Adaughter,ofcourse,isactingwithin
herrights,asthelastingrelationshipsinÑAmisandAmilounÄand
ÑKingHornÄdemonstrate.Thefatheristyrannical,jealous,or
overlyprotectiveinobjectingtoheractions.)Mostsimply,the
absenceofthefatherorhusbandprovidesthewomanwithan
opportunityshewouldnotnormallyhave.Inthecaseof
ÑGenerydesÄ,theaudiencealreadyknowsfromanearlierpartofthe
talethatSerenydesbetraysherhusband'strustinhisabsence.

Itisnotimmediatelyclearwhythewoman'sattempttoseducea
guestshouldbeconnectedwithhuntinginMiddleEnglishromance.
Thereisarudimentaryparallelinthebehaviourofthewomanand
herhusbandorfather-whilehepursuesanimalsshepursuesmen.
Butthis,perhapstheclosestapproachtothelove-huntinMiddle
English,remainsimplicitandundeveloped.ThepoetsofÑGenerydesÄ
andÑAmisandAmilounÄconcentratenotonthenotionofparallel
pursuits,butonthesenseofopportunitytobeseized.Itis
possiblethattheyconsideredtheequivalenceofthetwotypesof
pursuittooobvioustorequirecomment,butitismorelikely
thattheyweresimplynotinterestedinit.Pursuitis,
surprisingly,theelementofthehuntgivenleastexplorationand
developmentinMiddleEnglishhuntingmotifs.

InbothÑGenerydesÄandÑAmisandAmilounÄweareawarethatdecorum
isallowedtolapseonlyoncethehunterhasleftthehouseor
