ÄÑGuyÄ,lines....;ÑIpomydonÄ,lines

E
Ächaracters.InÑSirLaunfalÄ,theheroencourageshisfollowersto
explaintheirshabbyattirebytellingthekingthatthey
encounteredsomemisfortunewhilehunting.ê03,38ÄThemotifofthe
unfortunatehuntissofamiliarthattheexcuseisimmediately
plausible:theassociationofthehuntwithadventure,whether
goodorbadinitsoutcomeissopervasivethatevenacharacter
withinaromancecanconstructhisfictionsaroundit.

Thehunt'svictim

Thehunt'svictimisamotifgenerallyperceivedtobemore
commonthanitinfactis.Inpart,thismaybebecausethe
boundariesofthemotifareindistinct.Wecouldsaythat,ina
sense,anyhunterwhoencountersmisfortuneduringahuntisa
victimofthehunt.Butmoreprecisely,weshouldconsiderthe
victimwhoischasedbythehunt.

ThismotifcouldbetracedbacktothefateofActaeonandthe
traditionoftheWildHunt,butapartfromthespecificreligious
connotationsofthetruedevelopmentoftheWildHuntinMiddle
English,aninfrequentsecularmotifofthehunt'svictimshifts
theemphasisawayfromthetraditionalconcernwithflight.
Maloryusesthemotiffourtimes,andineachcaseitisto
furtherthedefinitionofcharacter.Themotifofthehunt's
victimrangesinmoodfromthecomictothedeeplyseriousand
symbolic.BothLauncelotandTristrambecomevictimsofthehunt
whentheyareaccidentallyinjuredbyarrowsaimedatananimal.
Tristramiswoundedwhilehuntingbeforehisappointedbattle
withPalomides.Thissimplydemonstratesthewell-recognised
dangersofthehunt;littleismadeoftheincidentitself,
thoughitisrecalledlaterwhenLancelotissimilarlyinjured.
Lancelotiswoundedinthebuttockbyahuntress,alsobeforea
battle.Theepisodeiscomic,treatingthenarrativedetailsat
greatlength,andshowingLancelotberatetheclumsywoman.
However,Launcelotdoesnotgiveintohiswoundasreadilyas
Tristramandridessuccessfullyinatournamentsoonafterwards.
Theparallelincidentsservetoilluminatethedifferencebetween
thetwocharactersintheirresponsetotherandomnessof
adventure.Launcelotacknowledgesthatheisunfortunate,
recognisingtheroleofchance,"Imaycallemyselffthemoste
unhappymanthatlyvyth,foreverwhanIwoldehavefaynyst
worshyptherebefallythmeeversomunhappythynge"(III,p.1106,
lines4-7),whereasTristram,whoseaccidentwearetoldwas"by
mysfortune",seekstoblamePalomides.Launcelothasgreater
autonomyandwill"taketheadventure"onhisowntermswhile
Tristramdoesnotasserthiswillovercircumstance.The
differencebetweenknightsoftheRoundTableisseenintheir
reactiontoanadventure,forthatwhichisordainedisnotthe
wholebutonlytheinitialcourseofevents;itsconsequencesare
N038:004207980003
ÄThomasChestre,ÑSirLaunfalÄ,editedbyA.J.Bliss(London,
1960),lines165-74.

E
Äshapedbyandrevealcharacter.

Elsewhere,Maloryusesthemotifofthehunt'svictimtomore
seriousintent.TheepisodeofMark'sfindingthemadTristram-
whichalludestothemotif-isdiscussedindetaillaterinthis
chapter;itisfirmlylinkedwiththecourtlyassociationsofthe
huntandtheirimportanceinrelationtoTristram'scharacter.
Malory'smostpoignantemploymentofthemotifisinthetaleof
Balyn,theknightofthetwoswords,andismetaphorical.Ashe
approachesthecastlewherehewillfightwithandslayhis
brother,Balynignorestwowarningsinhisdeterminationtotake
theadventure("Imayenottornenowageyneforshame,andwhat
aventureshallefalletome,beitlyfordethe,Iwilletakethe
adventurethatshallecometome",I,p.89,lines2-4).Ashe
presseson,committinghimselftohisfate,hehears"anhorne
bloweasithadbenthedetheofabest.'Thatblast,'said
Balyn,'isblowenforme,forIamthepryse,andyetamInot
dede"'(I,p.88,lines10-12).Thesoundoftheendofthehunt
markstheapproachingendoftheadventureandoflifeforBalyn.
TheadventurehastakenBalyn,andhisdeathisnowcertain,
dictatedbyeventsandhisowncharacterwhichdetermineshis
responsetothem-"Merepenteth...thateverIcamwithinthis
countrey;butImayenottornenowageyneforshame"(I,p.89,
lines1-2).Adventureandthehuntareequated,Balynisthe
quarryofthehuntandthevictimoftheadventure.Againthe
motifcontributestothedepictionofBalyn'scharacter:heis
fullyawareoftheconsequenceofhisactions,andisimpelled
towardshisdoombyhisobstinatedeterminationto"takethe
adventure"toitsconclusion.

Otherwritersalludetothemotifofthehunt'svictimless
fruitfully.TheverseromanceÑWilliamofPalerneÄusesthemotif
twice.Inthefirst,theinfantWilliamis"tracked"whenstolen
bythewerewolf.Later,WilliamandMeliordisguisethemselvesin
bear-skinswhenescapingfromherhomeland;theyarechasedbya
hunt,butthepartyisdrawnoffbythewerewolf.InÑTorrentof
PortyngaleÄ,Desonellloseshersonstoagriffinandalion,
thenfleesinterrorfromahuntbeforebeingfoundbytheking
ofJerusalemwhoisalsoouthunting.ê11,39ÄNeitheroftheseromances
developsthemotiftoagreatdegree;theyreferobliquelytothe
traditionoftheWildHunt,andexploitthesamesentimentsof
