Thoughthemotifofthehunt'svictimwouldseemtobear
considerablepotentialforexcitingnarrativedevelopment,itis
largelyneglectedbyMiddleEnglishwriters.Whereitisusedat
all,itdoesnotenjoyprominenceinaromance.Itwouldappear
thatthis,alongwiththelove-huntandChrist'shunt,wasa
motifthatdidnotappealtothemedievalEnglishimagination.
Interestingly,allthreeofthesefocusonpursuitasthecentral
elementofthehunt,andpursuitandflightaremost
conspicuouslyignoredbytheMiddleEnglishwritersinfavourof
courtliness.

Thehuntandcharacter:definitivemotifs

Themultifariousassociationsofthehuntmadeitarichsource
forthewriterwhowishedtoconstructacharacter'skeleton'
whichhecouldgraduallypadoutwithflesh.Theambiguityofthe
hunt'sstatus,itsuneasycombinationofcourtlyfacadeand
primitivestruggleagainstnature,yieldedcontrasting
suggestionswhichweredevelopedintocorrespondinglycontrasting
characteristicsforthehunter.Theferocityoftheboar-hunter's
adversaryyieldsanauraofspecialbraveryforthehunter,while
thesaferandmoremannereddeer-huntcametoepitomisecourtly
delicacyandaccomplishment.Butcourtlydelicacydoesnotalways
siteasilywiththemilitaryqualitiesdemandedofahero,and
althoughsuccessfullyintegratedinthefiguresofthecourtly
hunterandtheproficienthunter,thedeer-huntersometimesslips
N040:000608870023
ÄInÑTorrentÄ,themotifrepresentstheextremevulnerabilityand
isolationofthewomancastoutfromhumansociety,butin
ÑWilliamofPalerneÄtheuseofthemotifissimultaneouslymore
comicandmoresophisticated.WilliamandMeliordisguise
themselvesasanimalsandareaidedbyawerewolf,partofa
complexinterplayofhumanandanimalqualities,ofwhichthe
huntisonlyapart.Briefly,allthe"good"charactersreject
normalhumansocietyatsomepoint;theyaredistinguishedby
theiruseofanimaldisguisesandtheirlifeoutsidethecourt
societieswhichareseenaspredominantlymalignant,corrupt
andunhealthy.ThepursuitofWilliamandMeliordisguisedas
bearsbythehuntingpartyisoneinaseriesofincidents
demonstratingtheferocityofhumanityandthenobilityofthe
part-animalcharacters.Thetransitionsfromhumantoanimal
andbackagainaremarkedbyactsofviolenceorspiteandof
compassionrespectively,andcannotbeeffecteddirectly;
William'smotherhastodisguiseherselfasadeerinorder
tocommunicatewiththelovers.Allencountersbetweenthe
part-animalcharactersandthecourtaremarkedbythehuman
barbarityexemplifiedinthehuntscene.Themotifofthe
hunt'svictimsformsapartofthiswiderexplorationofthe
behaviourofmentowardsoneanotherandtowardsanimals.

E
Äintoridiculeandparody.AswesawinChapter2,medieval
culturedemandedthathuntingoccupyasuitableplaceinman's
concerns.Thehunterwhorelinquisheshishuntingtopursuea
loveaffairorachivalricadventureisapplauded,buthewho
persistsinhisuntimelyleisureactivitybecomestheobjectof
scornandderision.Theparodictreatmentsoftheproficient
hunterfocusonthecharacter'sfailuretorecognisetheproper
placeofthehunt,introducingchargesofcowardiceand
foolishnesstoexplainthefault.

Ñ
ÄDefinitivemotifs(1):Militaryvirtueandthe'epic'boar-hunt

Onehuntwhichneverresultedinridiculeistheboar-hunt.The
heroicbraveryoftheboar-huntercanbetracedinClassicaland
Celtictraditions,andmanifesteditselftoointheconventional
adoptionoftheboarasthepersonalsymbolofawarrior.ê09,41Ä

Althoughtheassociationsofmartialprowessandbraveryarenot
diminishedinthemedievalportrayaloftheboar-hunt,thevery
precisenarrativestructurewhichevolvedinMiddleEnglish
depictionsofitrevealsacompactionoffurtherconnotations
intothesingleimage.InMiddleEnglishromance,theepic
braveryoftheboar-hunteristemperedwithcourtlyactivity
whichraisestheepisodefromsimplemonster-slayingtoa
demonstrationofsocialskillmanifestingthedifferentfacetsof
thehero'sexcellence.Theboar-huntisthususedtodefinethe
characterofthehunterintermsoftraditionalmasculinity,but
alliedwithcourtlyprowess.Considerablenarrativedevelopment
characterisesthemedievalmotif;itismarkedlymore'present'
intheforegroundoftheromancethanarethemotifsthatsimply
introduceanadventure.

Boar-huntsfallintotwocategories:thehuntforaninfamous
boar,andtheappearanceofaparticularlyfierceboarwhichhas
notbeendeliberatelysought.Struggleswithinfamousboarshelp
toenhancethecharactersofBevesofHamtoun,EglamourofArtois
andKingArthurinÑTheAvowyngofArthurÄ.ê05,42ÄInthelasttwoof
N041:005709310009
ÄMarcelleThiÈbaux,"TheMouthoftheBoarasaSymbolin
MedievalLiterature",ÑRomancePhilologyÄ22(1968-9),281-99.
Ontheboar-huntasanepicfeature,seep.289:"Thechivalric
herowilloftenpursuetheallegedlycourtlypastimeof
huntinginamannerthatrecallstheepicbusinessofwar.By
sendinghisheroonaboar-hunt,amedievalauthorprocuredan
especialsenseofmilitaryurgency."


