Äthese,thetaskisundertakenspecificallytoprovetheskillof
thehunter:Eglamourbecauseitisan'impossibletask'setto
testhisworthinessasahusbandforChristabell,andArthurin
ordertofulfilhisownproudvow.Itmaybethattheboar-hunt
servestoshowhowcertaintypesofmotivationcanachieve
greatereffectsthanwouldnormallybeexpected,sothepowerof
theking'sprideandofEglamour'sloveenablethemtoperform
theirtasksandaremanifestedintheiraccomplishments.Butin
eachinstance,thesuccessofthehunterestablishescertain
charactertraitswhichcouldonlyberevealedthroughaction.

Beves'sadventureisofadifferentnature,beingpromptedbythe
socialneedtoridtheneighbourhoodoftheboar.Itoccursat
thebeginningofBeves'schivalriccareerandestablishesnot
onlypersonalvalourbutasocialroleforBeves.Hisglorious
figureridingouttodobattlewiththebeastelicitsIocyan's
love,hissubsequentfightwiththeangryfosterswhofeelhehas
stolentheirthunderestablisheshimasavictorovermenaswell
asanimals,andhissuccessperformsausefulsocialfunctionin
endingthetroublesomemaraudingoftheboar.Theensuingbattle
withthefostersgivesBevesanopportunitytoexercisehisnew-
foundmilitaryskillsonhumanadversaries,andthoughhis
battleisunconventionalandnotchivalric,itisanimportant
stageinhisdevelopment.Thisisthesecondboar-huntinÑBevesÄ;
inthefirst,Beves'sfatherissenttohuntaboartoprovide
medicineforhiswifeandiskilledbyherlover.Herethedanger
oftheboar-huntisnotoftheusualkind,buttheconventional
associationsofthehuntdemonstratehisloveforhiswife:heis
willingtoundertakethenotoriouslydangeroushuntonher
behalf.Thisfirsthuntgivesaspecialsignificancetotheboar
theyoungBeveskillsashisintroductiontoheroism,
accomplishingagreaterfeatthanthatwhichdefeatedhisfather.

Whentheboarhuntedisnotaspecific,notoriousbeast,the
characteristicconnectionofthehuntwithadventureisalloweda
moredominantrole.Wecanlookattwoexamplesinwhichaboar-
huntleadstoameetingandinitiatesthemainadventureofa
romance.Inthesepoems,theboar'sabilitytorunbeforethe
huntersforalongtimeisemployedbythepoetstodraweach
herointoisolationpreparatorytotheonsetoftheadventure.
PartonopeofBloisiseventuallyledtoMelior'scastleafter
becominglostwhilehuntingaboar.Sincetheboarmustdisappear
intothewoodinordertoleadPartonopeintotheforest,the
poetintroducesthisepisodebyhavingPartonopefirstkill
anothergiganticboar.BythismeansheestablishesPartonope's
heroismwithamotifdefiningcharacterbeforeusinganarrative
motiftodrawPartonopeintohisadventure.IntheÑRomansof
PartenayÄ,theferocityoftheboarwhichkillsAmerieanddraws
RaymonddeepintotheforestdemonstratesRaymond'sheroism.A
furtherdimensionisaddedtothemasculinehero,however.
Raymondisshowntobegreatlydistressedbythedeathofhis
lord,althoughcompassionisnotgenerallyacharacteristic
affordedmuchattentioninthedepictionofamasculinehero.The
poetskilfullycombinestheconnotationsoftraditionalmasculine
Ävalourwithanelementofcompassionateinvolvementwhich
preparesthegroundforthemovingemotionalscenesandenduring
devotiondepictedlaterintheromance.

InÑGuyofWarwickÄandMalory'sÑMorteDarthurÄ,theplotismoved
onbytheboar-huntinanotherway.Guychasesalargeboarinto
aprivateforestandkillsit,butasaconsequencehasto
undertakefurtherbattles.Theboar-huntisGuy'slastknightly
combat(exceptingaminordragon-slayingincident)beforehis
marriagetoFelice.Theepisodewhichshouldheraldfulfilment
fortheromancehero,soonturnssour.Fiftydaysafterthe
wedding,Guyisfilledwithremorsethathisknightlydeedshave
beendedicatedtoFeliceandnottoGod.Heabandonsherand
theirunbornsonandlivesasChrist'sknight,acceptingno
rewardorfameandfinallylivingasahermit,onlyallowinga
reunionwithhiswifeafewminutesbeforehisdeath.Thehuntis
acrucialturningpointintheromance,andisthemostfully
developedofthefivehuntingmotifsinthepoem.Mostofthese
motifsconcernthehunt'sroleinchivalricadventure:threeof
theminvolvemeetings,andafourthestablishesanearlylink
betweenhunting,courtlinessandchivalrywhenGuywinsa
tournamentprizeofhuntingequipment.Beforetheboar-hunt,
therearenoassociationswithdangerorviolence,thehuntis
neversinisternorbringsmisfortune.Theboar-huntisthefinal
huntingmotif,anditendsinmisfortunewithunnecessary
bloodshedandacrimony,asignificantlydismalendtoanepisode
whichbeginsbycombiningepicfightandspectacularhunt.
PotentiallyanopportunitytocelebrateallaspectsofGuy's
chivalry,thecentrallypositionedboar-huntbecomesinsteada
turningpointintheromanceasthebasisandidealsofchivalric
conductarecalledintoquestion.The'epic'huntturnssour,the
occupationofhuntingisitselfdiscreditedandwithitthewhole
secularchivalricfabricoftheromancewithwhichitwas
associated.Theidealsandaimsofnormalchivalryarerealised
butthenimmediatelyshowntobevaluelessasGuyleaveshiswife
andson,rejectingworldlygloryandblissinfavourofamore
severeachievement.Theboar-huntanditsattendantbattles
preparethereaderforthisreversal,underminingthelight-
heartedheroismofGuy'searlierexploits,themartialand
courtlyaspectsofwhicharetraditionallycombinedintheboar-
hunt.ThesignificanceofandmotivationbehindGuy'sactions
changeradicallyafterthisreversal,thoughinsubstancehis
actionscontinuetobeofasimilartype.Guywinsdivinefavour
afterhischange,butthesecondhalfofthetaletreatsof
bitternessanddisillusionment.Itnecessarilyinvolves
considerablepaintoGuy'swife,sonandfriends,whichisnot
fullyreconciledwiththespiritualbenefitGuyderivesfromhis
change.Theboar-huntstandspoisedonthebrinkofGuy'sown
disillusionment,butmarksthebeginningofdisillusionmentfor
thereader,andappearstypicallyasafigureofallthesecular
courtlinesswhichhasgonebefore.Overall,theseveralusesof
thehuntinthepoemdemonstrateitsfickleness,turningfrom
fortunatetounfortunateassociationswithnoapparentwarningor
cause,andfollowtheromance'sdevelopingnotionofsecular
Ächivalry,frompleasantamusementthroughusefulaction,to
disillusionmentandreplacementwithanovertlyChristian
chivalry.TheÑGuyÄ-poetthusemploystheconventionalassociations
oftheboar-hunttoraisehisherotothehighestpointof
chivalricachievementbeforeimmediatelyturningtheconventions
againstthemselvesinamasterlyreassessmentofthechivalric
ethic.

Adifferenttypeofcharactertransformationismarkedbyaboar-
huntinÑMorteDarthurÄ.Here,though,themoveisnotfromthe
courtlyinstitutiontosolitude,butfrommadnessandsocial
isolationtowardsreintegrationinthecourtlyworldsymbolised
bythehunt.Lancelot'scharacterhasalreadybeenestablished,
andthehuntisusedtoshowthebeginningofhisreturntohis
formercharacterratherthantodefineitfromscratch.Whilemad
intheforest,Lancelotwitnessesaboar-hunt.Whenoneofthe
huntersdismountsandleaveshisspearnearhimLauncelottakes
thespearandpursuestheboarhimself,finallykillingitbut
beinginjuredintheprocess(II,p.821,lines1-20).The
incidentisbizarre,anddoesnotsharethecarefullyplanned
plausibilityofMalory'sotherusesofhuntingmotifs.Notonly
isitincongruousthatthemadmanshouldentertheviolenthunt
andactasaconventionalwarriorhero,buttheeventsleadingup
toLauncelot'scombatareextraordinary,leavingmanyquestions
unanswered:whyshouldthehunterdismountandallowthemadman
totakehisswordandhorse?whatbecomesoftherestofthe
huntingparty?howcanLauncelotovertaketheboarwhenthe
houndscannotandtheprevioushunteronthesamehorsecould
not?Suchanomaliesinanarrativearecharacteristicofdreams
withinMalory'swork,butnotofhisportrayalofactionwhichis
tobetakenliterally.Heretheysuggestthattheepisodeis
symbolic.ThehuntoccursjustbeforeLauncelotbecomesthefool
atthecastleofCorbynwhereheisfinallyrecognisedbyElayne.
Inhiscombatwiththeboarandhissubsequenttreatmentofthe
hermit,theformerchivalriccharacterofLauncelotandhismad
personaarecombined.Thehunttestifiestohisfundamental
bravery,strengthandconventionalheroismpreparatorytothe
recognitionofhisintrinsicqualitybythecourtofCorbynwho
"thoughttheyneversawesogoodlyaman"and"demedthathehad
beneamanofworshyp"(II,p.822,lines31-5).

Betweentheboar-huntandtheidentificationofLauncelotthe
expressionofhismadnesschangesform,beingatonetimea
resultofhispainfulinjury,atanotheraresultofhishunger
("fordefauteofsustenauncehewaxedmorewooderthanhewas
aforetyme"II,p.822,lines16-18).Afterthisheisdressedandtreated
asafoolbyothers,butthisinvolveshiminarecognisablerole
incourtlysocietyinwhichhismadnessisgivenanacceptable
externalexpression.Hisreintegrationintochivalricsociety
beginswithhisinvolvementinthehunt,acivilisedoccupation,
andprogressesthroughhisadoptionasafoolwithitsattendant
courtlyclothesandacknowledged,thoughlow,status,tohis
finalrecognitionandhealing.Theactofhealingisitself
magical,ametaphorfortheincomprehensiblereturnofsanity,
Äbutithasbeenpreparedforsubtlybythenarrativein
Launcelot'sreintroductiontonormalsocietyanditscourtly
activities.

Theextendednarrativeattentiongiventotheboar-huntin
medievalromanceallowedthedevelopmentofarecognisable
structurerepeatedfromoneexampletoanother.Thedepictionof
theboar-huntisverystylised;itadaptsrealhuntingpractice
toamplifythebraveryandstrengthofthehero,andcombines
elementsfamiliarfromthetraditionalpatternoffightsbetween
twowarriorswithelementsfromthecourtlyhunt.

Theboarisinvariablykilledbytheherowithaswordandon
foot.Thisisclearlymoredangerousthankillingitwitha
spear,whetheronfootoronhorseback,whichwascommon
contemporarypractice.TheÑLivredechasseÄacknowledgesthatit
ismorenobletokilltheboarwithaswordthanwithaspear,
"letuerdel'espeesoitplusbelechoseetplusnoble"(ch.53,
p.231),butacknowledgesthedangeranduncertaintyoftackling
theanimalonfootwithasword:"S'ilveultdescendreauxabaiz,
c'estplusse¸rechosedel'espieuquedel'espee."(ch.53,
p.232:Ifhewishestoalightattheabay,aspearisamore
certainaidthanisasword).Intheromances,theactofkilling
aboarwithaswordmagnifiesthecourageandstrengthofthe
hunter,stressinghismasculinequalities.Thereisnoevidence
tosuggestthathuntingtheboaronfootwithaswordwasever
practisedasademonstrationofvalourinreallife,anditwould
havebeenlessthanprudenttoattemptsuchadisplayofbravado.
Inthemajorityofinstances,thelackofrealisminthisdetail
isnotofanygreatinterest,butinthecaseofBertilak'sboar-
huntinÑSirGawainandtheGreenKnightÄthetechniqueiscombined
withhighlydetailedandrealistichuntingscenes.Theeffectis
tomagnifystillfurtherthevalourofBertilak,forhereisa
hunterwhoisinmanyrespectsveryrealandyetisstillcapable
ofthemythicalactofslayingtheboaronfootwithhissword.
TheremovalofBertilakfromtherealmofconventionalromanceby
theotherwiserealisticdepictionofahuntenhancestheeffect
ofthisaccomplishment.

Stylisationextendsfurtherthanthemeansofslaughter,however.
ThepatternofeventsinÑBevesofHamptonÄrevealsastructure
whichunderliesalltheboar-huntmotifs,comprisingelementsof
battleandelementsofcourtlyprocedure.Thebattlesequencehas
sevenprincipalstages:

1)Thechallenge
2)Thecomingtogetherofmanandbeast
3)Thebreakingofthespear[anddeathofthehorse]
4)Thedrawingofthesword
5)Theprolongedfight
6)Thehero'sprayer
7)Thedeathoftheboar

Thispatternhasstrongechoesoftherepetitivepatterningfound
ˇÄinportrayalsofbattlesbetweenhumancombatants.ê04,43ÄInÑSir
EglamourofArtoisÄthehunterisonhorsebackandtheboarkills
thehorse.Allstagesarepresentexceptthefirstandlast.The
AvowingofArthuralsoinvolvesthedeathofthehorse.Before
thecombattheboarwhetsitstusksandrumbles,threateningthe
king.Thefighttakesplaceinsixstagesand,iftheboar's
threatisconsideredachallenge,theencounterisascompleteas
thatinÑBevesÄ.Ineachromancetheheroisbroughtneartodeath
duringthebattle,asinconventionalhumancombats.

Theencounterbetweenmanandbeast,thoughportrayedlikea
battle,ispresentedwithinthestructureofahunt.Hunting
procedureformstheprologuetotheencounterandisresumedwhen
theboarisrituallydecapitatedandbrokenup.ThusBevesarms
himself,ridesintotheforest,blowshishornandseekshis
adversary,thenfindstheboar'sdenlitteredwiththebonesof
itspreviousvictims.AfterthecombatBevesdecapitatestheboar
andsetsitsheadonthetruncheonofhisspear.Heblowsthe
prisetoannouncehissuccessandreferstotheepisodeas
hunting:

ﬁanneasettehorntomou˛e
Andblew˛eprisasewelkou˛e,
Sogladhewasforishonting.(lines829-31)

AsimilarstructureappearsinÑTheAvowingofArthurÄ.Theking
declareshisintentionintheterminologyofthehuntandsets
offwithhishounds,whichareattackedbytheboar.ê04,44ÄTheking's
responseistousetheappropriatehuntingtermstoencouragehis
hounds(lines169-71).Afterkillingtheboar,thekingundoesit
properly(lines254-62).

InÑSirEglamourofArtoisÄ,theframeworkofthehuntisreduced.
Theboar-andhart-huntsaretaskssettoEglamourinorderto
defeathimandsofrustratehisintentionsofmarryingChristabel
andareequatedwiththeothertasks,killinggiants.The
etiquetteandassociationsofthehuntplayonlyaminorpartin
thetwohunts,butaresuperficiallymaintained;afterkilling
thehart,"ﬁepriseheblewefullschyrlle"(line300,Cotton
MS),andEglamourandtheking'sknightsundotheboar
traditionally(line490).

Thepatternofanepicbattleinterpolatedintoahuntisvaried
whentheboarisnotaparticularlynotoriousanimal,butthe
