Definitivemotifs(2):Tristan,Ipomadonandthefigureofthe
proficienthunter

Incourtlyliterature,thegoodknightisinevitablyaproficient
hunterandhuntingformsapartofhiseducationevenwhenitis
nottobesignificantlaterinhisstory.Therearetwotypesof
referencetothefigureoftheproficienthunter.Byremarking
thattheheroisanaccomplishedhunter,anauthorcanrapidly
attributetohimthecourtlyskillsandprowessasawarrior
whichdistinguishthegreatknight.Suchacommentmayappearto
beathrowawayline,abriefobservationwhichbringstothe
characteraseriesofassociationsandskillswhichthereadercan
immediatelyappreciateandapprove.Butofmoreinterestthan
thistypeofcommentaretheromancesinwhichthehero'shunting
skillplaysanimportantpartintheplot.Ipomadon,Tristanand
RoswallinÑRoswallandLillianÄaresuchfigures,andalthough
huntingisimportantindifferentwaysineachcharacter'sstory,
therearesignificantsimilaritiesinitsuse.

Thesethreearethemostinterestingusesofthemotifofthe
proficienthunter.Theproficienthunterisalwaysaparagonof
knightlyvirtueandthereforeworthyoflove;theprincessof
CalabrialovesIpomadonmorewhensheseeshisproficiencyin
hunting,andIocyanfallsinlovewithBevesasheridesoutto
huntthegreatboar.Herethehunterrepresentsthecompleteand
perfectknightanditisthisfigurewhichrightlyinspireslove
ratherthanspecificallyhisproficiencyinthehunt.Othertexts
mayuseahero'shuntingskilltogiveaplausiblereasonfor
itemsinthenarrative,ormayincludehuntingskillinan
accountofafigure'sachievementsasabriefandeffectiveway
ofevokingafullcourtlycharacter.ThusSirDegrevant'sloveof
huntingexplainswhyhehasfinehuntingparksandisdrivento
violencewhenaneighbourdestroystheminhisabsence,andin
Lydgate'sStEdmundtheproficienthunter,Lothbrocus,is
murderedbythejealousBern,whoresentshispopularityand
success.ê03,47ÄOntheotherhand,thenarrativefunctionof
Bertilak'shuntingproficiencyinÑSirGawainandtheGreenKnightÄ
isquiteseparatefromtheaimofshowinghimtoberobustand
proficientincourtlyskillsbythethreehuntingscenes.Even
thepooradaptationÑTheGreneKnightÄretainsthehuntingskillof
theGreenKnightalthoughthehuntsarereducedtolittlemore
thanaformulaicexpressionofhispreoccupationduringthe
seductionofGawain.

ThemostfamousofallhuntersinmedievalliteratureisTristan.
Referencestohisexpertiseasahunterareoftencasual,
suggestingthathisreputationwaswell-establishedandfamiliar.
