Äpartofalargercourtlymilieurelatedprimarilytoleisure
activity.Further,Tristan'sstoryisonewhichtakesplaceon
themarginsofchivalriclife:itisconcernedwiththepursuits
ofnobleleisure,ofwhichlove,huntingandmusic(anotherof
hisskills)areparamount.Theimportanceoftheseactivities,
whichareusuallyperipheraltothemainactionofchivalric
romance,isheightenedastheycometodominateTristan's
character.LoveisexploredinTristan'sstory,whereasinmost
romancesitisaspurtoactionbutisnotextensivelydeveloped
itself.Tristan'sinvolvementinloveandhuntingbothdefines
thecourtlysettinginwhichtheactiontakesplaceand
precipitatesmajoractionwithinthepoliticalandmilitary
sphereswhicharegenerallyconsideredmoreimportant.

ThestructuralroleofhuntinginTristan'slegendisalso
noteworthy.Thehuntingskilldemonstratedearlyinthestorybecomes
importantlaterwhenTristanhastoliveintheforest(insome
versions,byhuntingforfood).However,thisisnotsufficient
toexplaintheemphasisonTristan'sroleasahunter.Gottfried
inparticularisconcernedthathisabilityisnotconnectedwith
hissurvivalintheforest,stressingrepeatedlythatinthe
minnegrottethelovershuntonlyforpleasureastheydonotneed
toeat.Thatthefirstepisodeprefiguresalaterconcernwith
huntingissignificantinanotherway.Severalversionsofthe
legendinvolveincidentswithalatercounterpart,eachoneof
thepairedepisodesaffectingourinterpretationoftheother.
Forexample,insomeversionsTristan'sstepmothertriesto
poisonhimwithapotionwhichismistakenforwine,clearlya
distortedanalogueofthelove-potionmistakenforwinelater.
RecognitionofTristan'sswordisimportantattwoturningpoints
inthenarrative,andTristanistwicewoundedbyapoisoned
spearandseeksIsolt'said.Someversionshaveanotherhunting
incident:Tristan,hidinginabushreadytomeetIsolt,is
almostdiscoveredwhenastagMarkishuntingshiesawayfromhis
hidingplace.ThisisreversedlaterwhenastagMarkhuntsleads
himtotheminnegrottewheretheloversliesleeping,andthis
timeitisMarkwhoshiesaway.Inbothincidentsthestag
apparentlydoesTristanagoodturn,perhapsbecauseheaffords
thegameduerespectandgivesititsrightfulplaceinanatural
scheme.Thesepairedepisodeshelptounifythestory,andatthe
sametimegivenewinsightsintothemeaningofthemotifs.The
secondtimeamotifisused,resonancesofthefirstcolourour
understandingofit,andwerecallthefirstmotifwithanew
angleonitsinterpretation.TherepeatedreferencestoTristan's
huntinggivethehuntcumulativemeaningandassociationswhich
areboundupwiththethematicconcernsofcorrectnessand
courtliness.

Thetwoprincipalhuntingincidents,theinstructionofthe
CornishmenandMark'sdiscoveryoftheminnegrotte,framethe
mainbodyofthelove-storyinthetextsoftheThomasbranchof
thelegend.Thetwocounterpointedepisodeshighlightachangein
Tristan'spositionfrommasterhuntsmantothepreyofcourtly
hunters-thecompanionofthedeerwhoistrackedbyMarktohis
Älair.(Insomeversionshishideawayismarkedwithabranchor
turfasthehuntingmanualsinstructthehuntertomarkthe
hart'srestingplace.)Thecourtlyartsofwhich
Tristanwasmasterarenowgone-hisloveisbeyondthebounds
toleratedbypolitesociety,andhehasbecomethevictimofthe
courtlyhunt.(InEilhart'spoem,hishuntingsinksfromits
courtlystatustotrappingandtheÑarcquinefautÄ.)The
correspondencebetweenhuntingandloveascourtlyrefinementsof
twobasichumanneedsisimportanttotheTristanlegend;the
sophisticatedhuntingwhichoncedistinguishedtheherofrom
