well,heblowshishornandcommandshisknightstotakeTristram
andcarryhimtothecastle.Tristram,oncethesupremecourly
hunter,isreducedtothestatusofananimalinthisscene.He
isdevoidofbothreasonandclothes,theinternalandexternal
distinguishingmarksofman,andissoughtandfoundwithinthe
contextofahunt.Mark'scourtlinessismanifestedinhis
hunting,andtheconfrontationbetweenthemadTristramandthe
courtlyhunterismadeallthemorepoignantbyourawareness
thatitwasTristramwhointroducedthearttoMark'scourt.Not
onlydoesMarkseekTristraminthecontextofahunt,buthe
blowshishuntinghornwhenhefindshisquarry-foramomentwe
mayalmostimaginehewillhuntTristram-andhisfallfrom
graceiscomplete.Thetransitionfromprincipalhuntertoprey
isthemostdrastictransformationpossibleforTristram,andthe
mostdisturbingforamedievalreaderwithahighlydeveloped
senseofman'splaceinthehierarchyofCreation.Thisepisode,
althoughdevelopedwithintheframeworkofaconventional
narrativemotif,isatoncedisturbingandironic;thenarrative
functionofthemotifisalmostnegligible;insteaditisthe
emotionalandimagisticreverberationswhicharethesourceof
itspower.ThisisconsistentlythecasewhenMaloryusesthe
conventionalhuntingmotifswithanydegreeoforiginality:the
primarynarrativefunctionisalwayssubordinatedtothe
symbolic,comicordefinitive,thelinearactionofthescene
madetoserveadifferentfunction,creatingmoodorfeeling,
commentingonordefiningcharacter.

Thehunter'spriorities:

InneitherincidentmentionedabovedoesTristramemergeas
particularlyheroic:hefailstosaveIsoldefromabduction,and
missesdoingbattleforher,bothonaccountofhisdevotionto
thehunt.Thisintroducestheflipsideoftheproficienthunter,
theaccusationsofcowardicewhichmayaccompanyparticularskill
inthesport.Thepossibilityofthisinterpretationofhis
Äskill,thesuggestionthatheeschewsadventureanddangeron
accountofit,isacknowledgedinMalory'stext,andarticulated
byIsolde:

"A!sehowsirTrystramhuntythandhawkyth,andcowrythwythina
castellwythhyslady,andforsakythus.Alas!"shallsomsey,
"hityspytÈthateverhewasknyghtoreverheshuldehavethe
loveofalady."(II,p.839,lines34-5andp.840,lines1-2)

ThisisverysimilartoEnide'scomplaintinÑEricetEnideÄ,and
isachargelevelledalsoatIpomadonandRoswallintheverse
romances.Here,thearticulationofIsolde'sfearhelpstodefuse
theaccusationbeforeitcanbemade,andtodenythatTristram
iscowardly.Insomeothertexts,theproblemisnotsolvedas
easily.

InthevariousversionsofÑIpomadonÄ,thesuggestionofcowardice
istackledhead-on.Ipomadon,hearingofthebeautyofthe
princessofCalabria,goestoserveinhercourt.Hemakeshis
markasabrillianthunter,andthecouplefallinlove.However,
theirloveisunacknowledged.Theprincessisunwillingtoadmit
herfeelingsbecausesheoncemadeaproudvowtomarrythe
greatestknightintheworldandIpomadon,thoughclearlya
paragonofcourtlybehaviour,showsnoproficiencyinbattle.His
skillinthehuntattractsherattentionandaffection,butitis
notaccompaniedbytheothertraditionalchivalrousskills.He
leaveshercourtandscornsherforseveralyearsashe
establishesachivalriclife.Later,heenterstheserviceofthe
kingofSicilywhereheisregardedasafoolbecauseofhis
devotiontothehunt.Heestablisheshimselfasaskilfulhunter,
demandstobeknownastheloverofthequeen,butshowsno
interestincombatorreallove.Throughouttheromancehe
retainsthispose,andfewcharactersseehistruevalue.He
eventuallywinsthehandoftheprincessbytakingpartsecretly
inatournamentdecreedtoforcehertoselectahusband.Hegoes
indisguisetofight,pretendingtothecourtthathegoes
huntingwheninfacthetakeshishoundstoahermitinthe
forestwhohuntsforhim;hisenthusiasticaccountsofhis
successinthehuntingfieldarethinlyveiledallegoriesofhis
conductinthelists,butheisridiculedmercilesslyforhis
lackofinterestinthecontest.

Alaterromance,ÑRoswallandLillianÄ,makesuseofthesame
motifs,withaherowhorejectsmilitaryendeavoursinfavourof
huntingandisscorned,andwhoeventuallywinsthehandofhis
belovedbyfightingindisguisewhilepretendingtohunt.
However,thesubstitutionofthehunterishandleddifferentlyin
thetworomances.ÑIpomadonÄdescribesindetailthehuntshe
pretendstohaveundertaken,whereasÑRoswallÄdoesnotdevelop
thematall.ThedetailsÑIpomadonÄgivesrepresentmetaphorically
thefighthehasengagedin,butdonotdescribetherealhunt
undertakenbythehermit.Themetaphorreducesthetournament,
associatingitwiththefollyofIpomadon'shunting,andsuggests
onhispartacasualanddetachedapproachtothebattlewhich
Ämagnifieshisprowess.Tothereader,thescenesindicatethat
forIpomadonthetournamentiseasy,asleisurelyashishunting,
whiletothecharactersintheromanceheappearsasincreasingly
foolish.ThispreparesforthereductionofIpomadon'senemies
andcolleagueswhenheisfinallyrevealedasthevictorious
knight.

Bothtalestacklethesubjectofhowhuntingcanbebotha
laudablecourtlyachievementandyetanindicationoffoolishness
andcowardice.Thetrueassessmentoftheactivityreliesupon
itsappropriatenessatanyonetime,andthepriorityitis
given.Ipomadonappearstotakehisloveofthehunttoan
extreme,refusingtogiveprecedencetomartialdutiesand
servinghisbeloved.Hisobsessiveindulgenceinaleisure
activityandhisapparentfailuretorecognisethecorrectorder
hisprioritiesshouldtakerightlybecomeasourceofmockery.
Roswallsimilarlyattractscensureforhisrefusaltorecognise
thepriorityofloveandwaroverhunting.But,atthecrucial
momentbothRoswallandIpomadonfightindisguisewhile
pretendingtohunt.Theheroisthusabletopreserveanairof
indifferenceandindependenceofpopularopinionandconvention.
Heretainshisindividualitymanifestedinthisidiosyncraticand
comicpreferenceuntiltheveryendoftheromancewhen,witha
flourish,heisrevealednotonlyasanon-conformistbutasa
supremelyefficientconventionalknight.Inthiswayheholdsour
interestwithoutultimatelydisappointingorfrustratingour
expectations.ForIpomadonthisisallpartofavengefulgame
andtheschemeofprioritieswhichplaceshuntingabovethe
tournamentheisexpectedtofightisneverseriouslyendorsed.
However,inRoswall'scaseitisslightlydifferent.Onthefirst
dayofthetournamentRoswallgoestotheforest,genuinely
intendingtohunt,butencountersthreeknightswhomhefreed
fromhisfather'sprison.Theknightsoffertohuntforhimso
thathecanenterthelistsindisguise.Roswallhasnowayof
knowingthattheknightswillcomeandhuntforhim;itispurely
bychancethathemeetsthemandsoisabletoenterthe
tournament.HisrefusaltofightforLillianandtoprovehis
loveandskilldonotrecommendtheherotous,anditisonly
throughthechanceappearanceofthethreeknightsthatheis
savedfromridiculeandestablishedasahero.Theromancecomes
dangerouslyclosetosacrificingthereader'sconcernforRoswall
asheinvitescondemnationwithoutofferingcomedy.

ThechastehuntercutsalessdramaticfigureinMiddleEnglish
literaturethanhedidasthetragicfigureofHippolytus.
Insteadofdefendinghischastityandhishuntingtothelast
againstsexualtemptation,hishuntinggiveswaytolove
whenthehunterbecomesmature.ThusDegrevant,depictedfirstas
aproficienthunter,fallsinlovewiththedaughteroftheearl
whodestroyshishuntingparks,andhisdesiretohuntleaves
him.WalterintheÑClerk'sTaleÄsimilarlyabandonshuntingwhen
hefallsinlovewithGriselda.Huntingandlove,althoughstill
portrayedasincompatible,arenolongermutuallyantogonistic,
butratherthehuntgiveswaytothemoreimportantbusinessof
Älovewhentheheroisreadyforsexualinvolvement.TheClassical
motifisadaptedbythemedievalauthorstoreflecttheirown
attitudestowardsthehunt.Insteadofdedicatedmilitaryprowess
andfiercelymasculinepride,themedievalchastehunteris
simplyimmature,andwhentherightwomanpresentsherselfhe
rightlyabandonshisstubbornrejectionofloveinfavourof
hunting.Thisformspartofthemuchlargerconcernwiththe
appropriatenessofhuntinganditscontext,itsplaceina
character'sprioritiesandthealternativeactivitiesavailable
atanytime:ifthealternativeistolove,toengageinwar,or
toundertakereligiousduties,huntingistoberejected,butif
thealternativeisidlenessorsin,huntingisthewiserchoice.

Parodiesoftheproficienthunter

Anauthorcouldeasilyshowthecourtlinessofacharacterby
referencetohuntingskill,andconsequentlyhuntingskillbecame
afeaturewhichreadilylentitselftoparody.WhenChaucer
createstheludicrousfigureofSirTopas,skillinhuntingis
oneofhismanyandvariedattributes:

Hekoudehunteatwildedeer,
Andrideanhaukyngforriver
Withgreygoshaukonhonde;
Thertohewasagoodarcheer;
Ofwrastlyngwasthernoonhispeer...(lines736-40)

However,hedoesnotquitemakethegradeasaheroridingoutin
searchofadventure,forheridesthroughtheforestwithout
hunting,passingbysuitablequarry:

Heprikeththurghafairforest,
Therinneismanyawildebest,
Ye,bothebukkeandhare.(lines754-6)

Huntingskillisonlyatinypartoftheparodicdepictionof
Topas,buttwopoems,theÑTaleofKingEdwardandtheShepherdÄ
andtheburlesqueÑHunttyngoftheHareÄ,havehuntingskillas
theircentralmotifs.Theanti-herooftheÑTaleofKingEdwardand
theShepherdÄisaproficientpoacherwhoboaststoacharacterhe
meetsontheroadofhisskillattakingrabbits.ê04,55ÄThe
characterturnsouttobetheking,andtherusticisduly
punishedforhispoaching.Thetalecondemnsboastingratherthan
poaching.Someoftheconventionalcharacteristicsofthemotif
oftheproficienthunterarereversedtoincreasethecomic
effect:thecourtlyhunterisreplacedbyarusticpoacherand
thenoblequarryisreplacedbytheignominiousrabbits.However,
theridiculetowhichIpomadonandRoswallaresubjectedis
