Thefifteenth-centurypoemtheÑHunttyngoftheHareê07,56Äisa
mock-heroicaccountofabattle;awholevillageandahundred
viciousdogsfailtocatchasinglehare,andreceivevarious
injuriesintheprocess.Ithaslittletorecommendittothe
modernreader,beingtoolonganddiffusetosustainitslimited
comicappeal.Themock-heroicaspectisdissipatedbyan
excessiveemphasisonnamingallthecharacters;probablythe
nameswereknowntotheintendedaudienceandthecomedyofthe
piecelayinthemockeryoffriendsandneighbours.Thehunt
itselfismerelyavehicleforachronicleofthevillagers'
incompetence,althoughthetriumphofthehareexploitsa
sympatheticattitudetowardstheprey.Thiskindof'sillychase'
isnotreallyahuntingmotif,butisperhapsbettergroupedwith
otherpursuits,suchasthechaoticchaseforthefoxattheend
oftheÑNun'sPriest'sTaleÄ.

Courtlyassociationsofthehuntinsecularandreligious
contexts

Wehaveseeenthatthehuntmaybedevelopedatsomelengthor
usedrepeatedlytogiveaspecialstatustoacharacter,oreven
toriudiculehim,butitmayalsobeusedonlyfleetinglyto
bestowcourtlystatusonacharacterorsociety.Itisthenstill
bebeingusedtohelpdefinecharacter,butinamuchmore
generalway.Innarrativeusesofthehunt,thefactthata
characterishuntingwhennotdoinganythingelsemarkshimasa
suitablecourtlyherofortheforthcomingadventure.But
sometimes,insteadofintroducinganadventure,thehuntisused
onlytobringthesecourtlyassociationstoacharacter,ortoa
society.Thereissomeoverlapbetweenthesecularandreligious
motifsinthisarea,astheuseofthehunt'sassociationwith
worldlypleasuresisawidely-usedmotifinreligiouscontexts.
Theexamplesdiscussedbelowuseonlythesecularaspectsofthe
hunt'sassociations,butthenextchapterconsidersalsosome
episodesfromverseromancewhich,thoughthemselvesinasecular
context,aremorecloselyrelatedtothereligiousmotif.


Theassociationofhuntingwithcourtlyandnobleleisureappears
inmanyguises.Inreligiouscontexts,theostentatiousnessof
theactivityisoftentakenasanemblemofasinful
preoccupationwithworldlyvanities,particularlyifinterestin
