Äthehuntisseenasreplacingdevotionorreligiousduties.In
secularworks,themostfrequentreasonforappropriatingthe
spectacleofthecourtlyhuntistoenobleafigure,showinghim
ascourtly,noble,elegant,sophisticatedandcivilised.Little
narrativedevelopmentisgenerallygiventohuntingmotifsof
thistype.Instead,thebriefestevocationofthehuntistaken
tosuggestthewholerealmofcourtlyactivityandbehaviour
availableornaturaltothehero.


Huntingwasacknowledgedasaproperactivityforgentlefolkboth
infictionalandnon-fictionaltexts.ThecourtesybookÑLytel
JohnÄstatesplainlythatthisisthecase:

Imyghthauesaidhesholdgohauke&honte
Forthatsholdbeagentilmansgametosuchdisportesgentil
folkesbewonte.ê03,57Ä

Intheverseandproseromances,thisisexpressedintheuseof
huntingasaleisureactivitybylaudablecharacters.Often
appearingasatime-fillingactivityforaheroabouttoembark
onanadventure,thehuntunderlinesthenobilityofthe
characterwhoengagesinitatappropriatemoments.Inthisrole,
itisoftenpairedwithhawking.Insteadofthehuntbeing
interrupted,asinthe"unfortunatehunt"and"meetingwhile
hunting"motifs,thehuntthenfillsafixedspaceoftime,the
necessaryintervalbeforeapre-arrangedevent.ThusSirTriamour
andArduspassthetimeinhuntingandhawkingafterTriamour
arrivesandbeforethedayappointedforTriamour'sbattle.ê02,58Ä
InÑYwainandGawainÄ,thetimeafterYwain'smarriageandbefore
hisdepartureisspenthuntingandhawking.ê03,59ÄInÑTheSiegeof
JerusalemÄ,Vespasianandhiscompanionspassthetimehuntingand
hawkingwhiletheRomantroopstrytostarvetheJewsoutof
theircity.ê04,60ÄInthelatter,huntingmarkstheRomantroopsas
admirablecivilisedChristiansinthesamemouldasmedieval
noblemen.Thedisparitywhichwemightfeeltoexistbetweenthe
"civilised"activityofhuntingandthebarbarousactofstarving
theJewswhilethemselveshavingagoodtimewouldnothave
disturbedamedievalreader,thoroughlyconvincedoftheevil
natureoftheJews.Instead,thecourtlyhunthelpstounderline
