ÄthedifferencebetweentheChristiansandtheirnon-courtly
enemiesandhelpstointegratetheRomanex-paganVespasianinto
theworldofthemedievalcourtlyromance.

Butsuchleisuremustbeappropriateifitistoescape
condemnation.Thehuntmustberecognisedascourtly,assport
ratherthanasautilitarianoccupation,butitmustalsobe
fittedatanappropriateplaceintoaschemeofprioritiesor
values.Thismaybeusedtothehero'sadvantage,asinÑGuyof
WarwickÄwhenGuyrefusesanearl'sofferofhuntinggearand
leisureinfavourofleavingtoseektoestablishhisprowessand
hisworthinessasahusbandforFelice.Theoppositeeffectis
achievedinÑPartonopeofBloisÄwhenPartonopespendshisyear
withMeliorhuntingduringthedaysandmakingloveduringthe
nights.Althoughforalongtimeheishappy,itisimpliedthat
somuchleisureisunproductive.LikeChrÈtien'sErec,hecan
onlystagnate,neverprosper,inthissterileandeasilyattained
blissandheisforcedeventuallytoloseituntilhehasearned
it.ThesuggestionisthatPartonopedoesnotlearnorachieve
anythingduringthisyear.Whenheiseventuallybanishedfrom
Melior'skingdomheisthrownoutinthehuntinggearinwhichhe
arrived,theimplicationbeingthathehasmadenoprogressand
isstillatthebeginningoftheadventure.

Thecourtlyassociationsofthehuntmaybeextendedtodepicta
lifestyle.WhenAmisandAmilounareadoptedandarefree"to
rideanhuntingvnderriis"(line136),thehunt,redolentof
courtliness,isemblematicofthecourtlinessoftheirnewlife
andthecharacteroftheiradoptivehousehold.TwiceMaloryuses
thehunttosignifythenormalcourtlylifefromwhichinsane
charactersareexcluded.InthecaseofTristramithighlights
thechangeinhisstate,butforLancelotengagementinthehunt
marksthebeginningsofreintegrationintocourtlysociety.A
contrastbetweencourtlylifeandthoughtsofdeathisfound
frequentlyinareligiouscontext,butevenintheverseromances
thehuntsometimesemergesinthisrole.WhenthekingdiesinÑLe
BoneFlorenceofRomeÄhiscourtiersmournhisdeathwithlaments
forhisgenerosityingivingthemhuntinggearandothercourtly
accoutrements,signifyinghiscourtlynatureaswellas
munificence.ê02,61ÄThekingoftheÑSquireofLowDegreeÄtriesto
bringhisdaughterbacktoanappropriatecourtlylifestyleafter
thesupposeddeathofherloverbyofferingherthechanceto
hunt,buthuntingandmourningareincompatible,asweshallsee
later,andheisunsuccessfulinhisattempttomakeherforget
herlover.ê02,62Ä

Conclusion

N061:001218710002
ÄÑTheBoneFlorenceofRomeÄ,editedby

N062:001018760002
ÄÑTheSquireofLowDegreeÄ

E
ÄWehaveseeninthischapterthattheusestowhichhunting
motifsareputbytheauthorsofMiddleEnglishtextscanbe
dividedapproximatelyintonarrative,character-definingand
associativefunctions.Themostprevalentmotifsarethosewhich
evokethehuntonlybrieflyanduseittointroduceanadventure
ornewdepartureinthenarrative.Thehuntisinthiscaseoften
interruptedandleftbehindassoonasnewconcernspresent
themselves.Occasionally,huntswhichintroduceanewadventure
areboar-hunts.Inthiscase,theyserveanadditionalfunction,
thatofestablishingtheprowessandbraveryofthehunter.The
boar-huntusuallystraddlesthecategoriesofnarrativeand
character-definingmotifs,thoughsometimesitisusedonlyto
definecharacter.Suchhuntsareusuallytreatedatlengthandin
detail,asthehunter'sgoodcharacteremergesfromtheskilland
couragewhichheexhibitsinthehunt.Alternatively,proficiency
inthehuntmaybeadistinguishingcharactersticofaromance
hero:TristanandIpomadonarethemostfullydevelopedexamples.
Inthesecases,whereamorecompleteanalysisoftheroleofthe
huntisrequired,considerabledetailisoftenincludedinthe
author'streatmentofthechase.Theemphasisonthehunt'slinks
withadventureissubstantiallyreduced.NeitherIpomadon'snor
Tristan'sstoryismuchconcernedwiththerandomeventswhich
contributetoadventureandareelsewhereassociatedwiththe
vulnerabilityofthehunter.Thehuntisinsteadconnectedwith
courtlinessand,particularlyinIpomadon'scase,withthe
foolishnessofaschemeofprioritieswhichovervalueshunting.
Thehuntingcharacterinliteratureisexpectedtoabandonthe
huntwheneveramoreimportantconcernisencountered-itmaybe
theopportunityforlove,ormartialexploits-andwhenhedoes
notacknowledgethecorrectplaceofthehuntheisridiculed.
Theanomalyofthecourtlyyetfoolishhunterandthemixed
feelingsheinspiresistreatedatlengthinÑIpomadonÄ;thefinal
deviceofthesubstitutehuntertakingoverwhiletheherofights
inatournamentallowsexpressionofhis
excellenceasbothahunterandwarriorsimultaneouslyand
demonstratesthattheyarenotmutuallyexclusive.
Ñ
IpomadonÄcontainsdetailedandaccuratedescriptionsofhunting
techniquewhichareanimportantpartofitsminuteandbeautiful
evocationofthecourtlysetting.Thepoemcelebratesand
displayscourtlylife,revellinginsuchdetailforthesakeof
itsintrinsicaestheticappeal.Thehuntscenessimilarly
contributetotheevocationofthemilieuinÑSirGawainandthe
GreenKnightÄand,thoughmoresophisticatedaspectsofthepoets'
useofthehuntdominatecriticalinterestinbothpoems,this
functioninÑSirGawainÄandÑIpomadonÄremainsimportant.Both
romancesuse(andindeedpromote)theassociationofthehunt
withcourtlinesswhichiselsewhereusedbrieflytoattribute
particularqualitiestocharactersorsocieties.Initsleast
sophisticatedform,thisinvolvesoccupyingsparetimewitha
hunttodemonstratethechivalricvirtueofacharacter,and
theseassociationsextendalsotothenarrativemotifs,building
upthehunterinoureyesbeforeheevenembarksuponan
adventure.Elsewhere,though,itmaybeusedmorethoughtfully,
ÄastheauthoroftheÑSiegeofJerusalemÄusesittoalignthe
earlyRomanswiththeidealsofmedievalchivalry,orasMalory
usesittosymbolisethenormalcourtlysocietyfromwhichinsane
charactersareexcludedandagainstwhichtheirdemeanedstate
maybecompared.Theusesofthehunt'sassociationswithnormal
courtlyactivityarethuswide-rangingandpervasiveinthe
seculartextswehaveexaminedhere.Nowweshallturntothe
huntingmotifswhichoccurinreligioustexts,anditwillbecome
obviousthattheseassociationscontinuetobeimportant.Indeed,
thedominantroleofthehuntinreligiouswritingsisto
identifythecourtly,secularwayoflifewhichitrepresentsin
theverseandproseromances.Theambiguousstatusofthehunter
whichwehaveseenparticularlyinthecharactersofIpomadonand
Roswall,andtheconcernwiththecorrectplaceofthehuntina
hunter'sschemeofprioritieswillemergeasdominantissuesin
religioustreatmentsofthehunt.

